Project 1: Cardio Good Fitness Project¶

Name: Adam DiStefano

Date: March 2022

Subject: Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Problem Statement¶

Explore the dataset to identify differences between the customers of each product. You can also explore relationships between the different attributes of the customers. You can approach it from any other line of questioning that you feel could be relevant for the business. The idea is to get you comfortable working in Python.

You are expected to do the following :

  1. Come up with a customer profile (characteristics of a customer) of the different products.
  2. Perform univariate and multivariate analyses.
  3. Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the company in targeting new customers.

Data Dictionary

  • Product - The model no. of the treadmill
  • Age - Age of the customer in no of years
  • Gender - Gender of the customer
  • Education - Education of the customer in no. of years
  • Marital Status - Marital status of the customer
  • Usage - Avg. # times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week
  • Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit)
  • Income - Income of the customer
  • Miles - Miles that a customer expects to run

Multivariate Analysis¶

In [ ]:

We will visualize these below.

In [ ]:
#Catplot of fitness and miles by product
sns.catplot(data=data, x='Fitness', y='Miles', hue='Product');
  • Customers who rank themselves least physically fit (1-2 ratings) exclusively use the TM195 and TM498 models of treadmills
  • Customers who rank themselves most physically fit (5 rating) almost exclusively use the TM798 model
  • Customers running the most amount of miles use the TM798 where customers running the least use the TM195 and TM498
In [ ]:
#Catplot of fitness and miles by product, broken down by gender
sns.catplot(data=data, x='Fitness', y='Miles', hue='Product', col='Gender');
  • More males than females rank their fitness higher, run more miles, and almost exclusively use the TM798
  • Women who rank themselves lower in terms of fitness (1-2 rating) use the TM195 and TM498 models, respectively.
  • Significantly less women use the TM798 as compared to men.
In [ ]:
#Catplot of fitness and miles by product, broken down by marital status
sns.catplot(data=data, x='Fitness', y='Miles', hue='Product', col='MaritalStatus');
  • Fitness ratings of 3 or less (whether single or partnered) almost exclusively use the TM195 or TM498 models.
  • More single customers with a fitness rating of 3 use the TM798 than the partnered customers with the same fitness rating.
  • There are more partnered couples using the TM798 wh rank there fitness level a 4 or 5.
  • Partnered customers with the highest fitness score run more miles.

  • Customers with 12-13 years of education do not use the TM798 model

Conclusions and Recommendations¶

  • Given that men rank their fitness levels higher than women, and cutomers with higher fitness levels exclusively use the TM798 model, the company should market their TM798 models to men who rank their fitness levels 4 or 5.
  • Since 98.7% of the customers have a college education, this should be the target demographic.
  • The vast majority of customers intend to use the treadmill between 2-4 times per week.
  • Customers earning less money are more likely to purchase the TM195 or the TM498 models. Perhaps offering a buyback program or upgrade incentives would helo customers purchasing the TM195 model to consider purchasing the TM498 (which is likely more expensive but most likely will result in higher profits).
  • Market the TM798 model to customers who expect to run more miles.
  • Based on the observations, men purchase more treadmills than women. It may benefit to build a marketing campaign targeting women.
